        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(signal): guard containerRestRequest JSON.parse against malformed responses",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\n`extensions/signal/src/client-container.ts:262` calls `JSON.parse(text)` on the Signal REST container response body without try/catch. The body is already bounded by `readProviderTextResponse` (16 MiB shared provider cap), but a malformed JSON body within that cap still throws unhandled `SyntaxError` → process crash.\n\n## Changes\n\n- `extensions/signal/src/client-container.ts`: wrap `JSON.parse(text)` in try/catch → `Error(\"Signal REST returned malformed JSON\")`\n- `extensions/signal/src/client-container.test.ts`: tighten existing malformed JSON test assertion to the specific error message\n\nLabel: bugfix | merge-risk: 🟢 minimal | AI-assisted\n\n## Evidence\n\n### Unit test — exercises actual code path (L2)\n\nThe existing vitest test `containerRestRequest edge cases > handles JSON parse errors gracefully` sends a malformed JSON response through the actual `containerRestRequest` function via `vi.mocked(fetchWithTimeout)`. This exercises the exact changed try/catch code path — the mock returns `new Response(\"not json\", { status: 200 })`, which flows through `readProviderTextResponse` → `JSON.parse(\"not json\")` → the new catch block.\n\n```\n$ pnpm exec vitest run extensions/signal/src/client-container.test.ts\n\n Test Files  1 passed (1)\n      Tests  53 passed (53)\n   Start at  17:50:32\n   Duration  18.28s\n```\n\nThe assertion was tightened from generic `.rejects.toThrow()` to `.rejects.toThrow(\"Signal REST returned malformed JSON\")`, proving the catch block produces the intended stable error message rather than a raw SyntaxError.",
